He acknowledged “angst about the state of our athletic department” and said he has “focused internally,” working with staff, student-athletes and supporters to commit to a “culture steeped in integrity and excellence.”

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Final: No. 13 Florida State 90, Northwestern 52

Hailey Weaver (12 points, 13 rebounds) had a career day, but the Wildcats never led. FSU had four players with 11 or more.

The Wildcats suffer their second significant loss to a ranked team, and fall to 3-2.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Florida State has its largest lead of the game, up 26 with 6:24 left.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
End of the third quarter: Florida State 63, Northwestern 40

Hailey Weaver has a double-double with 10 points and 11 rebounds, scoring eight points in the third. But every time NU tries to mount something, FSU has an answer.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
The Seminoles have gone cold, making just one of their last seven shots, but it's still an 18-point game at 4:18 mark of the third.

Hailey Weaver most recently cashed in with a three off an FSU turnover.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Florida State augments the lead to 22, entering a 8-0 run to start the third quarter. 'Cats call timeout.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Several Wildcats are in the thick of the playoff hunt with their NFL teams, making big plays to secure huge wins.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Halftime: No. 13 Florida State 41, Northwestern 27

The Wildcats posted more on the scoreboard in the second frame than the Noles, and have outrebounded FSU, but it's still a 14-point game.

O'Mariah Gordon leads all scorers with 11, while Paige Mott has eight for the 'Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A three from Carla Viegas halts some purple momentum and makes it 35-23 Florida State.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Jasmine McWilliams adds four quick points off the bench, but the hole is still 32-18.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Just like that, FSU has gone on another 7-0 run. Seminoles lead 30-12.

Content:
End of the first: No. 12 Florida State 23, Northwestern 8

Taking on the Seminoles is tough enough, but the 'Cats have made just 16% of their shots. Caileigh Walsh is 1-for-4, while Melannie Daley is 1-for-3.

Alexis Tucker has eight for the Noles.

Name: Inside NU

Name: Inside NU
Content: Caroline Lau hits two free throws, and the 9-0 FSU run is finally over. It's still an eight-point game, though.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Seminoles lead 12-2, in part because Northwestern has gone three-and-a-half minutes without a score.

Name: Inside NU
Content: From the HAT to Dakota Marker to even his go-to Thanksgiving plate, hear what David Braun had to say at his weekly presser yesterday.

Name: Inside NU
Content: An 18-year-old school record broken, historic relay splits and standout performances mark Northwestern swim and dive’s outing at the Purdue Invitational.

Name: Inside NU
Content: At long last, the construction of a new Ryan Field — with associated concerts — can commence.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That wraps up Braun's media availability.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
On defensive scheme: "The non-negotiables is going to be, making sure the scheme fits our personnel, fits our players."

"Guys get themselves into trouble when it's, 'Guys, this is my defense.'"

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on if NU will hire a full-time DC: "I will not be calling defensive plays next year."

Said he will for Illinois and the bowl game, but that it's "not in the program's best interest" to do so after that.

"It would be selfish on my part."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
"I've always felt that my success as a DC is a reflection of having the right room of coaches. It's my job to create a collaborative environment."

Called McGarigle a "critical piece" to success and performance.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Tim McGarigle: "All you've got to do is sit in on one of our defensive staff meetings."

Praised Matt MacPherson, Christian Smith, LaMarcus Hicks and others, not to mention GAs.

"We have an incredible room. It's a collaborative environment. Great teachers."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Added that certain players will have decisions to make about whether or not they want to return.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on leveraging rotations in recruiting: "I think it reflects, if we're going to talk about being a developmental program, then our actions better align with that. In some ways, it's forced development."

Talked about "trust" and "willingness," plus earning chances.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun says that "conversations have tended to trend in the right direction" regarding prospect invitational games. Mentioned that he hasn't directly talked to Jim Nagy.

"There's no doubt that there's a lot of guys on this team that have put a lot of good things on tape."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Echoed that "there was a confidence and a belief that this group could do something really special," but that it was largely on the inside.

Praised stories that have "put on display what this group has done."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on doubters: "Honestly, that was never a motivating factor. For those that looked at me that way, from the outside looking in, I don't blame people for having that reaction."

Talked about how Skip Holtz and D.J. Vokolek "entrusted this program."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on his energy levels: "I promise you my vertical won't get me recruited anymore."

Asked himself, "Hey man, are you really being you," after the Duke game.

"Just show up as the best version of yourself each and every Saturday."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun called Hollis Jr. "one of the best corners in the country."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Garnett Hollis Jr.'s tackle: "Garnett was our Defensive Player of the Week. Some of it had to do with his interception. A big part of it was that effort play. It was an incredible play; even better effort."

Noted improving consistency and practice habits.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun praised Braden Turner and Evan Smith for their special teams contributions.

"It's your proving ground that contributes to confidence."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on special teams: "It's absolutely critical. It's complementary football. It's all three phases."

Talked about there being a "mishap" on the first extra point, but lauded Will Halkyard for "flushing that."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on his Thanksgiving plate: "I don't think I've met a food on Thanksgiving that I didn't like. The hard part is how you fit it on one plate."

Talked about mashed potatoes, stuffing and turkey.

"Don't count out a dessert."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Carmine Bastone: "I'm just really proud of Carm. I'm proud of the way this program operates. For him to just continue to improve...and produce."

Noted that it's "no surprise" based on his practice habits and efforts.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the defense: "We did not play at our best. We have to play better. Sometimes in modern football, people get tied up in yards, but the only thing that matters are in the wins and lost column. If we thought we didn't have to improve this week we'd be kidding ourselves."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on preparing for two quarterbacks: "In some ways, we're dealing with a similar set of circumstances."

Noted that Luke Altmyer and John Paddock have "played at a high level" despite having somewhat different skillsets.

"That can create some issues in your preparation."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on possibly ending Illinois' season: "To be honest with you, it's not something that's on my mind, or that I'll be communicating with the team."

Emphasized "finishing off the regular season the way we set out to."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that he wants to make sure the HAT, as with any trophy, has a "comfortable place" in the facility.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "Rivalry games are always more exciting when there's more on the line. There's certainly a lot on the line this weekend."

Name: Inside NU
Content: "If you want to beat an in-state rival on some of those recruits...you better show that you're winning some of those rivalry games."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the best version of the Illinois: "At its best, you have two programs that are winning a lot of football games. That have great stories to tell. Not only to their own teams, but also on the recruiting trail."

Praised Bret Bielema's recruiting efforts.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Noted that being especially true in defensive prep.

"Probably in that Week One, I was trying to do it as I had always done it."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on his level or organization, Week One to now: "I think I've always felt comfortable from a standpoint of being with our players, stepping into a leadership role. Trying to bring people together. Where I think I've really grown is understanding where I need to delegate..."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun talked about the Dakota Marker between NDSU and SDSU.

"It's basically a really, really heavy rock. You better be prepped in the weight room to lift that thing over your head."

Name: Inside NU
Content: "There's just something about rivalry games, especially when you're playing for a trophy. Those games are things that stay with you as a player and as a coach. You can certainly sense within this group, especially within the upperclassmen."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on learning about the Illinois rivalry: "The consistent message is, 'Coach, we want the HAT back.' Just to see and feel and sense the urgency that's with this group right now to ensure we're at our best. One of the many things that makes college football so special."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun noted that the team doesn't care about where its recruiting class ranks, prioritizing work ethic and fit.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the '24 recruiting class: "It's unique with roster management right now. Everyone in the room knows, with still having guys on the roster having a COVID year. We probably have room for two more commitments in the class."

Emphasized "staying flexible."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Stressed that "messaging" remains largely the same.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on talking to recruits as the permanent head coach: "It changes from a standpoint of, you get less questions. There's a certain level of certainty in terms of the fact that, you make a decision to come to Northwestern. 'Hey, I'm going to be here for that.'"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Noted that "conversations...will start after Illinois."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said he's stressing "positions that are currently open" regarding his coaching staff.

"Those are things that we're taking a look at right now, to make sure that we can continue to push the program forward."

Said there's "too much at stake" to determine other things now.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "We're rolling. We're excited. Know that we've got  quite a challenge on our hands with a really good Illinois team fighting for bowl eligibility."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun noted that Northwestern "has fallen short in" the last few games against Illinois.

"We know that there's a lot of things that we have to clean up. Didn't play our best football on Saturday."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun's opening statement: "Really excited about the opportunities ahead of this team. Obviously, Saturday was an incredible opportunity for our guys to send the old Ryan Field off the right way."

Mentioned that it's "clear" that "we have a lot of work to do."

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun set to speak to the media, so make sure you get your cards ready.

Content: Walsh on her performance: "I didn't play a good game at Notre Dame, and I took that personally. I felt like things were working tonight, but I know that will not always happen, so I need to learn to play through adversity."

Name: Inside NU
Content: “For all of its flaws, Ryan Field will always possess an innate charm and quaintness... In lots of ways, that’s the exact essence that Northwestern football has carried with it for these 97 years,” writes  after Northwestern’s sixth win.

Name: Inside NU
Content: “It’s no small feat to immediately make your mark on a team full of accomplished veterans,” writes . “But that’s what Bent-Cole and Tromp have done their whole lives: inject pure energy and talent into each team they’re part of.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: For the final time in 2023, and probably for the last time in its current form, good night from Ryan Field.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern pulled away from Rhode Island for a 72-61 victory in the Hall of Fame Tip-Off. Here’s how the action unfolded:

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: NU 72, Rhode Island 61

Northwestern set the tone offensively in the second half, and pulls away from URI to go start 4-0 and set up a date with Mississippi State tomorrow afternoon. 

Three scorers in double figures: Barnhizer (18), Buie (16), Berry (13). Langborg had 9.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
With about two minutes to go, a big three and strip from Berry, as well as a one-legged fadeaway from Barnhizer, have Northwestern sitting comfortably with a 66-52 lead and 2:18 to go.

Northwestern looks like it's in prime position to start off 4-0.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern pulled away from Rhode Island for a 72-61 victory in the Hall of Fame Tip-Off. Here’s how the action unfolded:

Name: Inside NU
Content: That concludes today's pressers.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on the young guys getting an extra month of bowl prep: "Getting an extra month to spend with this team and these guys is awesome."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter: "It's a long game. Defense, they make adjustments. We make adjustments as well."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter on the HAT: "First and foremost, understanding the history of the game. How important it is for the university."

Talked about a "bitter taste" last year.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on playing with Braun as the full-time HC: "Not a huge difference. We bought in to playing for him the rest of the season beforehand. We knew he was going to be there for us."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter on differences from 2021-22: "I think as a leadership group, it's been a very big point on making sure that we're doing the little things right. Attacking each day with the mindset to get better. Practice habits turn into game habits."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller said he thought Purdue may have kicked, but that the team was "definitely was ready for it."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on the field-storming: "I thought they were going to take the goal posts down. It's good to be in the higher win column."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mueller on goal-line stands: "We knew we've done that before. Nothing changed. That's always the goal."

Stressed "complementary football."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mueller noted that McGarigle talked to the unit about "sending the seniors off the right way."

Porter: "As a group and as a team, we made a choice. Coming together. Understanding that every week is another opportunity to stay together."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mueller on dealing with a dual-threat QB: "We knew Card was a good runner, but a little bit less. Definitely a different challenge. Wasn't anything crazy."

Talked about dealing with Heinrich Haarberg in Lincoln.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter on Senior Day/playing the last game at Ryan Field: "It's hard to really explain how it feels. Currently, still taking everything in. It's a blessing. This is an awesome place."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mueller on his game-winning interception: "That was awesome."

Stressed LBs coach Tim McGarigle for helping preview that formation.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
MBB: Under-8 now, with Northwestern leading 59-48. Buie now at 11 points in the half. He's led a resurgent NU offense, which is holding off a great URI shooting display (5-of-6 from deep). 

The 'Cats are already in the bonus with 7:41 to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller on making stands: "That's a huge emphasis for us. If we don't allow them to get in the end zone, they can't win."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter on his day: "Offensive line was playing their butts off. Crease was there; was able to hit."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Xander Mueller and Cam Porter at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That wraps up Bryant and Johnson.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Johnson on the defense: "It gives us a ton of confidence. It allows us to play a little more free."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on taking care of the ball: "That was just really dumb by me. I didn't look off the safety. He read it well. Taking care of the ball is super important."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on student support: "It's meant so much. Obviously, you want the support of the students. It was really cool to see us supporting them all game. It was just a really cool way to finish it off."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Johnson on scoring in three straight: "I think just work. Constant work. Coming into practice every day. Finding ways to continuously get better throughout the year."

Talked about continuing to "go up the hill" and avoiding a "peak."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
MBB: Under-12: Northwestern leads 53-39. 

The offenses have begun to erupt. It seems like both teams have constantly answered each other with buckets these last few possessions... NU is shooting a sparkling 9-of-12 through eight minutes, and Buie has 7 in the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on playing Illinois: "Illinois never recruited me in high school, so I'm excited to show them what I can do."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Johnson on Braun having the tag removed: "It means a lot to me. He's one of the best, if not the best, that I've had in my time."

Praised the "voice he brings" and his "confidence."

"You can tell that he loves us."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Johnson on staying locked in for the finale: "We don't have to have a lot of conversations. It's Rivalry Week."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on winning two straight: "Being able to handle success. It felt like after we lose a game, we'd come back in the next week and have a great week of practice. This week, it felt like we had that same mentality."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on how he feels: "I feel good. I feel great. I'm ready to go for Illinois."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on dealing with pressure: "I don't think there was much adjustments. We said we were going to call some different things. Throw it up to this guy [Johnson]. I think the O-line did a lot better."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant called Senior Day a "poetic ending" living close to Evanston, and growing up watching NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Johnson said Senior Day was "definitely special."

"This has been one of my favorite places I've been."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant: "Our defense has been playing phenomenal. That just gives us so much confidence to go out there and play loose."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant says that he and the team "talked all week" about Purdue's safety blitzes.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Johnson on overcoming drops: "It was definitely lingering throughout the game."

Mentioned the touchdown helping erase it.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant on playing in a bowl game: "College goes by so quick. Now, it's about to be over. I'm super happy that we have that opportunity."

"For me, it's something that is super special," Johnson said, noting an injury his freshman year.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Johnson said he "definitely could have" anticipated having success.

"I had nothing but belief that we would do this."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on his play today: "I think there were some good things, but definitely some things I would want back. I'm super picky about myself. I can't turn a win into a loss."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ben Bryant and Cam Johnson now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That concludes Braun's media availabilty.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun mentioned a "couple missed fits...that really hurt us."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on not having a QB spy: "How they were doing things formationally was smart. Credit to them. There were certainly some adjustments, not only at halftime, but also throughout the second half."

Mentioned avoiding the scrambling hitting downhill, with mixed results.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Ben Bryant: "I think he started to get comfortable and make quick decisions. You also have to credit the people around him. You got to credit Purdue. Ryan is a hell of a ball coach."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on defensive versatility: "It allows you to be diverse in your play-calling. You're just trusting your guys to go play fast, play with great leverage."

Talked about discussions with NFL scouts.

"They're darn good football players."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
MBB: Under-16 has hit in the second half, with NU up 43-30. The 'Cats have started the second half well, with Barnhizer and Buie each hitting threes. 

Barnhizer, at 13 points and seven boards, is on double-double watch, which feels like the most inevitable thing ever.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that a "unique opportunity" was needed to remove him from North Dakota State, and that's what he got at Northwestern.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on his family: "It's all that matters. It's those people back home, and it's our student-athletes. All the other stuff is just stuff on the periphery."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Senior Day: "For us to have our last game here in the old Ryan Field, go down like this with securing bowl eligibility, is really special."

Noted that such a day is "hard," and praised the team for "resetting."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on running in the first vs. second half: "There's some adjustments. The other component of it is just staying the course. Trusting the run game."

Mentioned the need to "lean into efficiency," which "leads to explosiveness."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that, in some ways, fourth-down stops are "as good as" a turnover.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the team's defense: "I think we've embodied what great defense looks like. To us here at Northwestern, it's not the play-call. It's not some crazy ideas and game-planning."

Talked about leverage, fundamentals and tackling, plus takeaways.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Said the OL did a good job of "anchoring in."

Called the Cam Johnson touchdown "incredible recognition" by Ben Bryant.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on offensive line improvement throughout the game: "I think those two things [run game and OL] really complement each other."

Lauded Purdue's defensive structure, based in man and Tampa 2.

"They're going to pin them back up front, and try to take advantage."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun called the team an "energetic group" postgame.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on maintaining focus with bowl eligibility: "I don't want to take anything for granted, but I hope it's easy with the Land of Lincoln Trophy on the line."

Stressed "staying laser-focused."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the first half imbalance: "That's team football."

Mentioned the team "finding ways to stay in games" throughout the season, pointing to against Minnesota.

"We've got to continue to lean into that."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on if he envisioned going bowling: "Absolutely. At Big Ten Media Day, we talked about the goals and aspirations of what this group could do. I don't blame anyone, but I would be lying if there weren't eye rolls. It's a reflection of these young men."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said he'd refrain from commenting on if students should have laked the post after the win.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on students storming the field: "It's so cool. We've talked about it before in words. We've talked about the student experience. That's it embodied. It's awesome. That's what college athletics is all about: bringing a community together."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on his first game without the interim tag: "I don't know if it felt different. To be honest with you, I don't know if this will all completely sink in until the offseason."

Noted players' reactions after the win as being telling.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the play of seniors: "I think that's a reflection of what development really looks like. Guys that have really stayed the course."

Talked about Cam Porter's ability to overcome injuries, and Xander Mueller's growth.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "I can't tell you how overwhelmed with joy I am that this team has an opportunity to extend its season, get an extra game."

Noted that the "task is not done."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "A credit to Purdue. They battled. They did some really good things offensively. Moved the ball quite a bit effectively. Yards don't result in wins; points do."

Praised the defense for not breaking.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun's opening statement: "Definitely speechless this time. Been an incredible week in so many ways."

Mentioned the focus being on Purdue today despite being named head coach.

"I think it's an absolute reflection of just this team's maturity."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
HALF: NU 33, Rhode Island 26

Raining on the parade at home, Northwestern’s 22-2 lead gets significantly cut, punctuated by a half-ending foul by Buie on a URI three.

NU is shooting just 35% from the field despite going 40% from three. Barnhizer leads with 10 on 2-of-9.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Cam Porter’s big day, combined with strong goal-line defense, propelled Northwestern to its sixth win.

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun set to speak to the media shortly.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Purdue Pete may haunt you in your sleep, but he clearly didn’t spook the Wildcats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern fans storm the field after the team's sixth win in maybe its final game ever at Ryan Field.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Northwestern 23, Purdue 15

It was a lot closer than it should've been, but the Wildcats are officially bowl eligible.

Cam Porter (95 yards, two touchdowns) and Cam Johnson (88 yards, a score) helped lead the team to victory.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mueller picks off Browne, and that's it! Northwestern will win!!

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Heard stops Tracy in his tracks. Third-and-two upcoming, but the clock stops because of a Purdue injury.

28 seconds left after a 10-second run-off. Ball is at the Northwestern 34.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Miller is tackled in bounds, and the clock is running. Under a minute left.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
MBB: With under four minutes left in the half, Rhode Island has put a dent into NU's lead with an 8-0 (and 15-4) run. It's 26-17 NU.

The highlight of that stretch was a powerful block from Tyson Brown, who STUFFED Jordan Clayton and jumpstarted a Zek Montgomery fastbreak layup.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Browne locates Jaron Tibbs for seven. Then, Browne scampers out of bounds for another first down.

Purdue driving, at the Northwestern 42. 1:13 left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne races past Heard for a first down. Purdue at its own 48 with 1:34 left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Miller secures a fluttering pass for a gain of five.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Renner's punt slows down at the Purdue 38, where the Boilermakers will have it.

Eight-point game. 1:59 to go. Boilermaker ball. What does Northwestern's defense have as an answer?

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter is well short of the marker. Renner will punt, and Purdue will get the ball back down eight with over two minutes to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter makes a jump cut and gets four. Purdue is now out of timeouts, and will deal with a third-and-6 on the other end of the short break.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter loses his footing on first, and Purdue utilizes its second timeout. Second-and-10 upcoming with 3:02 to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Freehill's kick lands in the end zone for a touchback.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Terrific design by Purdue building off the toss. Burks gets the reverse and sprints for two.

It's 23-15 Northwestern with 3:06 left. Not done yet.

Name: Inside NU
Content: As if things couldn't get any better.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mockobee is in for six on a toss. It's 23-13 Northwestern, and Purdue will go for two.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mueller and Turner converge on Browne, and, wouldn't you know: it's another fourth-and-goal for Purdue.

Walters uses his first timeout of the second half. Biggest play of the day upcoming.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher helps corral Browne. Purdue facing another third-and-goal situation, down 16 with 3:25 to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne muscles his way down to the 3-yard line on a keeper.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tracy runs straight downhill past a cavalcade of black, and has a gain of 57. Garnett Hollis Jr. tracked him down at the 8.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne links with Burks to set up third-and-2.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne collects two on first down. Under 5:30 to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
With the ball at the Purdue 48, Bryant's throw for Kirtz is undercut by Thieneman for an interception.

Don't fully understand throwing in that situation. Ball goes back to Purdue.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
MBB: At the under-12, it's 16-2 Northwestern. Barnhizer punctuates what is now a 10-0 run with a three as the shot clock expires.

Rhode Island is a staggering 1-OF-13 from the field, and has turned it over four times.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Tyus is short on third down, but an unsportsmanlike conduct call on Purdue's Antonio Stevens keeps it Northwestern ball.

Unreal blunder by the Boilermakers.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Karlaftis makes the tackle on Tyus on second, bringing up third-and-5.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tyus is wrestled down for a minimal gain on first.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Browne looks deep, but Theran Johnson had terrific position to knock it away! The 'Cats get off the field, up 23-7 with 7:49 to go.

You can smell bowl eligibility.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mockobee gets seven, and it's fourth-and-10. Might be game.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
MBB: We're at the under-16, and Chris Lowery has taken his defensive talents out east. 'Cats lead 9-2, and have forced Rhode Island to start just 1-of-8 from the field. 

Buie leads all scorers with 5, including an impressive three-pointer in a defender's face.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne angles outside for three, and it'll be third-and-17 Purdue from the Northwestern 34.

Name: Inside NU
Content: False start on Purdue's Mahamane Moussa will spot the ball at the Northwestern 37.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Adeyi puts a stop to a quick Purdue pass to Tracy. Loss of two.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On third-and-2, Tracy has enough for the first down. Inside of 10 minutes to go, and Purdue is threatening.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne keeps it in his hands and gets six.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne dumps it off to Mockobee, who churns for 15 yards. Boilermakers at the Northwestern 44.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Browne scoots for 12 yards on first, and Mockobee follows it up with 11.

Jaheem Joseph, involved on the stop, slowly walking off the field.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A hold on the runback puts Purdue at its 18.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
MBB: Elsewhere, Northwestern men's basketball has just tipped off against Rhode Island at the Hall of Fame Tip-Off in Uncasville, Connecticut. Very occasional updates from us until football wraps up.

Starters: Buie, Berry, Langborg, Barnhizer, Nicholson.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Olsen converts the XP. Wildcats lead 23-7 with 12:08 to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter is left wide alone, and races untouched to the end zone! It's his second touchdown of the day.

Kirtz got into a scuffle with Derrick Rogers Jr., but the score counts.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant overshoots Kirtz, who ran a comeback. Bryant expected the fade.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter rushes for three on first down.

Name: Inside NU
Content: NU goes back to Porter, who works his way up the gut for a new set of downs. NU at the Purdue 37 with 13 minutes left in this ballgame, looking to tack on to a nine-point lead.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter collects nine on the next play.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant stands tall and hits Johnson DEEP for a 25-yard gain. What a pickup for the 'Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant steps up in the pocket but is off target to Johnson. It's third-and-6 for NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A.J. Henning is questionable to return with an upper-body injury, per Northwestern Athletics. Explains why we didn't see him on last the punt return.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
End of the third: Northwestern 16, Purdue 7

Still a sloppy one here from Ryan Field, but the Wildcats were lifted by a 52-yard catch-and-run from Cam Johnson.

One quarter left to enjoy this wild one (and this glorious stadium, in all likelihood).

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter veers for a gain of four, with Thieneman making another stop.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Kirtz makes a fair catch on the punt. No A.J. Henning this time.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Meredith tries to hit Sheffield along the sideline, but the receiver couldn't get a foot in. The Boilermakers will punt.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Pate works upfield to stop Tracy. It's third-and-5 Boilermakers as the third nears a close.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Jaylen Pate wraps up Meredith for no gain.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Olsen's kick is out of bounds, and it's another special teams mistake.

Purdue will start at its 35.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Touchdown, Northwestern!

Bryant hits Johnson on a curl route, and the receiver did the rest on YAC for a 52-yard score.

It's 16-7 'Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Himon makes one Boilermaker miss before getting only two. Wildcats at their 48.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mike Bajakian dials up a fake screen, then a real one to Himon. The RB works downfield for a gain of 14.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Himon gets tripped up after netting four.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Henning fumbles the kickoff after running it back, but Braden Turner picks it up. Near disaster.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Tracy bobs and weaves through multiple Wildcats, and Purdue has finally gotten on the board.

It's 9-7 Northwestern with 3:59 to go in the third.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Michael Kilbane helps bring down Browne for a tackle for loss. Purdue at the Wildcats' 20 with four minutes left in the third.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Purdue going tempo, and Mockobee has more than enough for the first down. He hurdles a defender all the way down to the NU 19.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne runs a draw for seven, which sets up third-and-3 from the Northwestern 33.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne throws outside for Jayden Dixon-Veal on first.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne looks to Mockobee down the seam, who hangs on through the contact. Purdue all the way down to the Northwestern 40 after the 26-yard pitch and catch.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ball stays with Mockobee, who collects only two. It's third-and-6 for the Boilermakers, trailing by nine.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne finds Mockobee for a gain of two, and a big hit by Heard follows.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne keeps the rock and runs off tackle for a gain of 12. Devin Turner with the stick.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tracy bobbles Jack Olsen's kickoff but recovers and runs it out to the 18.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Olsen makes from 30, and the Wildcats lead 9-0 with 7:38 left in the third quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Thieneman halts Henning on third, and Northwestern will elect to kick on fourth-and-1 from the Purdue 12.

David Braun opting for the conservative choice.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant looks to Tyus on a wheel route, but the pressure affected the throw. The 'Cats have third-and-6 from the Purdue 17.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Henning gets the carry and tries to work back, but Dillon Thieneman cuts him down for just four.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Sheffield drops Renner's punt, and the Wildcats recover! Greyson Metz got on it, and NU is at the Purdue 21.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant looks to Johnson outside, but it's incomplete.

Northwestern is 3-for-10 on third down. A stark difference from a week ago.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant dumps it off to Porter, and it's third-and-11 Wildcats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter picks up three to set up second-and-12. The 'Cats have 18 carries for 20 yards today, factoring in sacks.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A Josh Priebe false start immediately moves the ball back.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant locates Henning in the flat, and the senior surges ahead for a first down.

At long last, some offensive production!

Name: Inside NU
Content: Kydran Jenkins meets Porter immediately on second, and it's third-and-8 Northwestern.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Great breakup by Purdue's Markevious Brown to knock the ball away from Johnson on first.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Watching Northwestern and Purdue play today

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ansell's rocket of a punt trickles into the end zone.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
On third, Meredith scrambles, but a sea of black jerseys swallows him up.

Neither team has scored since the 11:40 mark of the first quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Meredith hits Miller for a loss of two. Seemed like weird timing on the manipulation. It's third-and-7 for Purdue.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Jaheem Joseph tracks down a Tracy toss for a gain of five.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Renner's punt is downed at the 37, where Purdue will begin the second half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant throws wide of Henning on third, and it's six straight drives with no points for NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant finds Henning for a gain of 12, and it'll bring up third-and-4.

Name: Inside NU
Content: A hold on Johnson negates a screen to Henning, making it second-and-16.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter starts the second half with a four-yard gain on a split zone.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ben Freehill's kick is fair caught by Henning for a touchback, and the second half is underway.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Just under 1,000 miles away from the action currently unfolding at Ryan Field, Northwestern men’s basketball will tip off a back-to-back. Here’s what’s on the line for the ‘Cats:

Name: Inside NU
Content:
HALF: Northwestern 6, Purdue 0

The Wildcats' defense bent but didn't break on multiple occasions, including stopping the Boilermakers from the 1. But, NU has plenty to clean up, having surrendered five sacks already.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Olsen misses the 38-yarder wide right. Just his second miss of the year.

That type of bizarre game so far.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant is sacked for the fifth time, and the 'Cats spike the ball with nine seconds left. Jack Olsen will come on for the kick.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant hits Cam Johnson for a gain of five, and NU utilizes its last timeout with 24 seconds left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Browne looks deep, but Garnett Hollis Jr. undercuts it for the pick! Wildcats have the ball at the Purdue 20. Great play in the Cover 2 defense by the CB.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Renner has a beautiful punt downed by Ray Niro III. Purdue will start at its 2 with 35 seconds to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Khordae Sydnor works right around Josh Thompson, and Bryant is sacked for the fourth time. Northwestern will punt.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant throws incomplete to Henning downfield. Strong coverage by Cam Allen.

It's third-and-18 from the Purdue 36 with 49 seconds left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Yanni Karlaftis dumps Bryant, and Braun calls TO. Third sack for the Boilermakers, and the 'Cats are at the PU 36 with 55 seconds left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant looks deep down the far side to Kirtz, who adjusts to make the catch! NU at the Purdue 28 after the 20-yard gain.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant gets decked on what arguably should've been a late hit, but he's staying in the game. It's third-and-4.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant throws outside the numbers to get four from Kirtz.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Richie Hagarty scooped it up for NU, and the Wildcats will start at their 40.

Name: Inside NU

Content: Jaheem Joseph *nearly* picks off Bennett Meredith on second down. Tremendous play by the senior.

Content: "We've honed on it all year," said Marshall of the defense. "Making big tackles outside of the circle."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Read everything David Braun, Michael Schill and Derrick Gragg had to say yesterday at Braun’s introductory press conference right here:

Name: Inside NU
Content: That's all from Braun, Gragg and Schill.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on reshaping the program: "I think we've had a similar conversation about the defense when we first arrived here. It's not about putting my stamp on it, at the end of the day, it's not my program, it's Northwestern's and our players."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on  what he's learned about himself the last few months: "I'm at my best when I'm rooted in my purpose, when I'm rooted in my faith, and I know who I answer to: my God."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "One of the gifts I've ever earned is an opportunity to win a national championship at NDSU. But you quickly realize after that experience that all is fulfilled completely. You better know your purpose. The opportunities that have come have come from walking in purpose."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on his long-term coaching vision: "I wanted to be the head coach at a Big Ten institution. That was my dream."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gragg on when he decided on Braun: "The timing on it, the president and myself... we wanted to relieve the pressure of what Coach was mentioning. We've been talking about this all season. I made the decision, but I had a lot of people to consult with."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on when he felt like he'd become the head coach: "Call me crazy, but it was like, wake up each morning, what do I need to do today to figure out what I need to do each day to get ready for Saturday.

"Honestly, it didn't become a reality until mid-week this week."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on when he learned he'd be the interim in July: "Don't know if it was something I was excited about, but honored to have an opportunity to be with these guys. I learned that there's a tremendous opportunity to have an impact on every person in the program."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on celebrating: "There wasn't much celebrating other than getting ready for Purdue, but there were certainly moments back at home."

Said the biggest celebration came at home with his sons when his sons said, "We're not moving!"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on what the players' support meant to him: "The support from our guys... it's why we do what we do. For these guys. It's not just the locker room in Madison, it's the way these guys showed up every single day."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun concludes his statement. Q&A portion has begun.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "You want to talk about the character of a team? All you've got to do is look at this group right now."

He notes a desire to use that character to "change the college football landscape" and "out-team" everyone in the country.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun briefly mentions long-term goals, then follows up with: "All I care about is having a great Thursday and beating Purdue."

Name: Inside NU
Content: "They've rooted back into their purpose: the young men that sit here today."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun thanks the staff.

"Character is revealed in difficult times. I've been unfortunate enough to be part of a staff that's been let go at UC Davis, and fortunate enough to be part of a staff that's won national championships [at NDSU]."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "Myself and our family know that the opportunity that exists for our family only exists because of you guys, and your willingness to buy in, and galvanize, and come together, and embody what this program is all about."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun thanks the players: "Words won't do it justice."

Said it was hard leaving NDSU and the relationships he made there, but "blown away by the quality of young men that make up this program."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "When this transition occurred during the summer, my wife eight months pregnant. We talk about not flinching... Kristin Braun never flinched."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun thanks his family. "Not just the last few months but the last 10 years."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Gragg: "He's shown tremendous leadership under these adverse circumstances and he embodies respect, integrity and excellence."

Noted Braun's body language, interactions w/ players, postgame messages. Said there was a "We Want Braun" chant in the locker room after Wisconsin.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gragg: "Would I ask this coach to lead and support my own children? Anyone who's done this knows we don't always get it right, but we certainly got it right this time."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Gragg thanks Braun's family for their sacrifice. He also thanked the student-athletes and the coaches for their resilience:

"I lost my coach senior year, and that pales in comparison to what they've gone through."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gragg now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Before handing the microphone off to Derrick Gragg, Schill noted that "he deserves a big thank-you" for playing "an integral role" in bringing Braun to Northwestern and helping make the decision to remove the interim tag.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Schill: "Dave I'm so proud to have you a part of the Wildcats family. I'm so proud of what our football team, our student athletes have accomplished this season."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Schill: "In the face of adversity, [Braun] has set an example for all of us that living our values as a university is a successful pathway to success by any standard."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Schill noted that he particularly saw Braun's leadership qualities observing him in the season opener at Rutgers.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Schill: "Big Ten football is under a microscope. But Dave came into a particularly difficult situation, and never wavered in his commitment to you."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Schill: "[Braun] has shown what it means to be a leader by acting as a resource for his student-athletes, by modeling incredible humility and by showing them that he is here to support them, to support you, in every phase of your development and all of the way."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Schill: "I am so happy to be celebrating the news that all of you have seen by now, that effectively former interim head coach David Braun will become the Jones Family Head Coach of the Northwestern Wildcats!"

Met by applause.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern's introductory press conference for David Braun has begun.  Michael Schill will talk first, followed by Derrick Gragg, followed by David Braun.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Here at Ryan Fieldhouse, where David Braun is set to be formally introduced as Northwestern's 30th head coach. Stay tuned for updates!

Content: There’s plenty to address after Northwestern’s large loss to No. 16 Notre Dame.

Content:
In their 11th game of the season, the Wildcats look to put together two wins — and clinch bowl eligibility.

Here’s what Northwestern will have to do to take down Purdue.

Content: Take a look at the teams who will challenge Northwestern’s quest to 22 straight victories and a championship.

Northwestern football answered its most important long-term question yesterday by naming David Braun its head coach.

But, as  explores, there’s a lot more to settle — as soon as next week, and especially in the upcoming months.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The ‘Cats allowed 110 points in Notre Dame’s home-opener:

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Notre Dame 110, Northwestern 52.

A very forgettable outing for the 'Cats, who turned the ball over 25 times and shot 34% from the field.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Notre Dame has eclipsed 100 points.

The Irish lead by 57 with a little under three minutes to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
The Irish won't let up. 

With eight minutes left in the contest and up 41, most of ND's starters are still in.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
In 2022, Northwestern lost by 34 to Notre Dame: 92-58.

The 'Cats currently trail by 37: 79-42. 

Can they crawl back in the fourth quarter to best their showing from last season?

Name: Inside NU
Content: Notre Dame has scored a buzzer beater in every quarter tonight. Wow.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
A very slow third quarter comes to an end, as the Fighting Irish lead the 'Cats, 79-42.

In 10 minutes, we saw 12 fouls, two hard hits and three team timeouts.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Paige Mott is subbed in and fouls out 13 seconds later.

She entered tonight leading the B1G in rebounds/game, but couldn't collect any against ND.

Name: Inside NU
Content: McWilliams puts up an attempt that's blocked, but she's able to grab her own rebound and convert on a second-chance layup.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Things keep getting uglier for the 'Cats.

After Maddy Westbeld collects an offensive board for the Irish, she's fouled by Jasmine McWilliams. 

After sinking both free throws, ND is up 70-32.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Hailey Weaver nabs her third three of the day. She leads all NU scorers tonight (11).

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mott gets called for an intentional foul, which sends Hidalgo to the line and gives ND the ball back.

Certainly not the start to the half that McKeown was hoping for.

Name: Inside NU
Content: (Not so) Fun fact: NU hasn't shot a free throw all night.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Worth noting that last year's contest between these two teams featured technicals and ejections.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Paige Mott sets a MEAN screen on Hidalgo that's called for her fourth foul of the night.

The refs are going to review it for a potential higher-level foul.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Daley gets the spark going, opening scoring for the second half.

She has 10 points on 5-for-13 shooting tonight.

Name: Inside NU
Content: ND misses its first shot of the third quarter. Good vibes incoming.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Kicking off the third quarter, and it looks like ND gained a point during halftime. Refs must've upgraded an Irish jumper to a three-pointer during the break. 

We'll kick off the half with the 'Cats trailing by 30.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Through 20 minutes, the killer has been turnovers for Joe McKeown's unit.

NU has given it away 15 times to ND's nine. Three TOs for the 'Cats in the final 3:25 of the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Make that a 12-0 run — forgot to include the last-second jumper.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Insult to injury: Citron hits another buzzer-beater to end the half.

The Irish end the half on a 10-0 run, and NU will head to the locker room down by 29.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
The Irish are *flying* right now. Gotta respect the pace.

They've used it to nearly double-up Northwestern — 51-26 with 1:07 left in Q2.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Back-to-back layups from Notre Dame makes it 47-26.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Impressive sequence as Prosper and Weaver trade threes. 

43-26, ND.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Daley misses a jumper and McWilliams misses the follow-up off the ORB.

Got to connect on the second-chance opportunities if NU wants to climb back into this.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Paige Mott gets called for a shooting foul and sends Anna Dewolfe to the line.

Dewolfe makes both, and the Irish are up by 17 with 4:11 left in the first half.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
After Hidalgo and Daley trade buckets, Citron sinks a three to win the sequence.

36-21, ND.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Out of the timeout, NU is called for an offensive foul. Ademusayo was moving on a screen. 

Not what the 'Cats needed to stop the ND momentum.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Consecutive layups from ND extend the Irish lead to 12. McKeown calls a timeout to regroup.

Notre Dame is shooting 60% from the field so far while Northwestern is hitting on 39% of its shots.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Hailey Weaver comes through and sinks a three.

The 'Cats needed that to keep up with a very quick Irish team.

27-19, ND.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Hannah Hidalgo makes a transition layup on a fast break. 

27-16, ND.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
After grabbing an offensive rebound, KK Bransford is fouled by Caileigh Walsh. She goes 1-for-2 at the charity stripe.

25-16, ND.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
A hectic start to the second quarter.

Jasmine Mcwilliams turns it over to start the quarter for NU. Then, Natalija Marshall makes a bad pass for ND. *Then*, Casey Harter turns it over again for the 'Cats.

Geez.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
A momentum-shifting end to the first quarter.

Melannie Daley misses on a jumper for the 'Cats with 13 seconds left in the period. Sonia Citron then connects on a three as time expires, dampening what had been a small NU run.

Heading into Q2, the Irish lead by eight — 24-16.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sonia Citron ends the 'Cats' short run and sinks a jumper for ND.

21-16.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Casey Harter turns a ND turnover into points for the 'Cats. 

19-16, Irish.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mercy Ademusayo makes a second-chance layup thanks to a ND turnover. 

Cuts the Irish's lead to five — 19-14.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Notre Dame is pressing now.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Kylee Watson grabs an offensive rebound and puts it back up, grabbing another bucket for the Irish. Brutal.

Now 19-12.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Anna Dewolfe scores on a fastbreak for ND, making it 17-12.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
McKeown calls his first timeout of the night with 3:26 to go in Q1. 

NU has kept it close so far, down only three after about seven minutes of action.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Back-to-back steals from Daley and Mott get the Wildcats back in it, as it’s now 15-12.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
A Caileigh Walsh foul sends ND to the line. 

Cassandre Prosper sinks both and extends the Irish lead — 15-8.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Notre Dame is on a 13-0 run in the last 2:05. 

It’s now 13-8, Irish, with 5:02 left in the first.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Just like that, Notre Dame takes the lead. 

A steal and a few threes later, the Irish are up by a couple in the middle of the first.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Notre Dame nails a three out of a timeout to get on the board. 

8-3, ‘Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
‘Cats are cruising to kick off tonight’s action against the Irish. 

8-0 a few minutes into play.

Content: Tonight’s starting five versus No. 16 Notre Dame.

Content: There it is. Northwestern confirms the earlier report by  that the full-time head coaching role will go to Braun.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Per reports, Northwestern football has appeared to drop David Braun's interim tag — and there wasn’t much surprise.

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun appears to have secured the full-time head coaching job. After taking over for Pat Fitzgerald as an interim in mid-July, Braun is set to become the program's 30th full-time head coach.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Now in the home stretch, there’s still movement in the Big Ten Power Rankings:

Name: Inside NU
Content: One win away from a guaranteed bowl game appearance, is it fair to think the ‘Cats are back?

Name: Inside NU
Content: There’s plenty to glean following another nail-biter against a major underdog:

Name: Inside NU
Content: That’s all for tonight’s availability.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie on flushing the game: "You flush it like you flush any other game. It doesn't matter if we won by 30 tonight, you have to move on and get ready for the next game."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Barnhizer on his defense: "It's just listening to our coaches. We get steals out of our philosophy."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie on if he felt added pressure to score: "No."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie on rebounding struggles: "I didn't think we did a good job at finding bodies and blocking people out. That can't happen. It was something that was discussed."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Barnhizer on scoring 20: "It felt good, but my head was in other places. I just wish we had played a more complete game."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie: "We showed some toughness grinding the game out. I didn't think we started the game well and that set us back. We need to be better next game."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Boo Buie and Brooks Barnhizer now at the podium

Name: Inside NU
Content: That'll be all for Collins.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on Mullins: "He just has to stay ready. His time is coming."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on getting the bigs going: "We want those guys to be opportunistic.  We want them to continue to work. We wouldn't have had the season we had last year if Matt didn't play at a high level, so we need to help him get back to that."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Colins on scoring: "We can't expect to win games with only Boo and Brooks scoring."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on eking out a win: "You always want to learn things while winning. If you don't come ready to compete every night, you can lose to anybody. We can lose to anybody. It was a step backward after a step forward."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "I don't think we came into this game with the mindset of being physical. It has nothing to do with the size, it has all to do with mentality."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on rebounding issue: "It has nothing to do with the size. We're not boxing out. We're not clicking. We need our bigs to rebound. It's a collective effort."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins: "It was one of those nights where the shots weren't falling, but that's part of basketball."

Emphasized that Western Michigan deserves credit.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins: "We're very fortunate to win the game. I told them that they deserved to win the game. Everyone knows that we weren't playing well. We were able to make a couple shots and make enough stops to win the game. We have a lot of things to clean up defensively."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Chris Collins now at the podium

Name: Inside NU
Content: Survive and advance.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Northwestern ekes out a 63-59 win over Western Michigan.

It was not pretty, but Buie and Barnhizer carry the Wildcats to a victory.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Martinelli pokes it away, and Barnhizer corals it and is fouled.

7.4 seconds remaining.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Langborg makes the second.

Two possession game.

Name: Inside NU
Content: First free throw is good.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Another offensive rebound for the Broncos, who convert it into a layup.

'Cats call a timeout up 61-59 with 20.6 seconds to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Refs say last touched by NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
WMU's three bounces around the rim and out, but the Broncos aren't able to corral the long rebound in bounce.

'Cats clinging to a 61-57 lead with 46.8 seconds left.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Kick ball probably saves a Broncos' basket.

Under a minute to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mad scramble for the ball finds Langborg, who drills a fadeaway as the shot clock expires.

Crowd getting into it as the 'Cats will try to hold on for the next 1:52.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Buie chucks up a prayer, and it somehow goes, but WMU responds with a three.

59-57 NU with 2:22 to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer is denied at the rim, but flies across the floor to grab the loose ball.

Pure hustle from the junior.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Preston gets called underneath for his third foul.

Western Michigan shooting from here on out.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Northwestern has 15 rebounds in the game.

Western Michigan has 15 OFFENSIVE rebounds alone

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Tie game for a split second, but Buie responds with a big three.

Pick-and-roll game is killing NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
'Cats catch a break on a bad pass by the Broncos.

NU clinging to a 54-52.

Name: Inside NU
Content: It's again a one-point game.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Northwestern's offense looks all out of sync.

Is Brian Ferentz calling this game?

Name: Inside NU
Content: Langborg finally gets on the board with a layup to expand NU's lead to 53-47 with eight minutes to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer pokes it away and goes coast-to-coast for the easy layup.

He now has 20 for the first time in his career.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Buie finally hits a triple, NU's first in nearly 15 minutes.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
It's a one-point game.

Broncos are on an 8-0 run and have possession at the under 12.

Northwestern is 4-21 from three today -- yikes.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Another offensive board by WMU, its 12th.

For comparison, NU has 15 rebounds in total.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Every time 'Cats get a bucket, the Broncos respond with one of their own.

44-38 Northwestern with 14:34 to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Berry is fouled going up and will shoot two after the timeout.

'Cats clinging to a 40-33 lead.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Nicholson picks up his third on what appeared to be a monster rejection.

Chris Collins did not agree with that one.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer has his first miss in six attempts.

I blame myself.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer with another and-one in transition, his third on the night.

Everything is falling for No.13

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Second-half action underway.

Starting five out on the floor for NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
At the half: NU 35, WMU 27.

It has not been pretty for the Wildcats, shooting 22.2% from three and being outrebounded 25-11, but their star duo of Buie and Barnhizer have done just enough to give them a slight edge.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer with another and-one with 3.3 seconds left in the half.

He has 13 points in the first half alone.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ryan Langborg is 0-6 in the first half.

Berry will come in to replace him with under a minute to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Buie has two straight triples rim in and out.

Just brutal.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
NU is now 4-13 from beyond the arc tonight, but multiple shots have rattled in and out.

'Cats still lead 30-26 with 3:30 left in the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Jordan Clayton gets his first collegiate points on a three-pointer.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Teams are trading long balls, and Collins calls a timeout to regroup.

27-26 NU with five minutes left in the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Nicholson picks up his second foul of the day, and we have reached the under-eight.

Wildcats lead 22-18.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
OH MY GOD BOO BUIE!

He splits to defenders and makes an acrobatic layup through contact for an and-one.

NU's top two scorers are coming alive.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer takes a massive hit, but somehow his mid-range shot falls and he converts the three-point play.

'Cats have their first lead of the night.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer pokes it away, and Martinelli finishes through contact at the rim, but can't convert the free throw.

'Cats down 16-14.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer finally gets on the board with a three-ball to cut WMU's lead to two.

Halfway through the first half, and Boo Buie still has not scored.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Not too shabby for a Tuesday night

Name: Inside NU
Content:
WMU works the ball around for an easy dunk down the lane, but Martinelli responds with a lay-in for NU.

12-9 Broncos with 12 minutes left in the half.

Chris Collins is not happy with his team.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Buie's three-ball rattles out, and Barnhizer misses his first shot from deep too.

'Cats are 1-6 from three.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Jordan Clayton checks into the game and finds Nicholson underneath for the two-hand jam.

The freshman is getting some early minutes for the Wildcats.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Langborg cannot connect on his first two attempts from beyond the arc, but the 'Cats defense has held WMU scoreless in the last three minutes.

NU trails 6-5 at the first media timeout.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
No shot clock violation.

WMU retains possession.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Appeared to be a shot clock violation, but referees say Broncos got the shot off and hit the rim before time expired.

Play is under review.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
'Cats turn it over on the first possession, and WMU cashes in from deep on the other side on back-to-back possessions.

On its third possession, Berry hits a triple of his own

6-3 Broncos.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Nicholson wins the tip and we are underway.

Content: ‘Cats are debuting their new gray jerseys tonight
