Content:
Tonight's starters for Northwestern:

G: Boo Buie
G: Ryan Langborg
G: Ty Berry
G: Brooks Barnhizer
C: Matt Nicholson

Small ball at its finest.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
‘Cats look to remain undefeated to start the season, hosting Western Michigan in non-conference action in 15 minutes. 

Follow along for updates.

Name: Inside NU
Content: For the third straight year, Northwestern will send a cross country runner to the NCAA Championships. Ava Earl led the way in Northwestern’s third-place finish at the Midwest Regional last Friday.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The Wildcats still have two games left, but are very likely to qualify for a bowl game.  explores where Northwestern’s most likely itineraries may be.

Name: Inside NU
Content: All that’s standing between Northwestern and a bowl game is Purdue.

Name: Inside NU
Content: As the ‘Cats prep for possibly the last game at Ryan Field, hear what interim head coach David Braun had to tell the media.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That ends today's Braun media availability.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on NU fans coming out: "Do everything you can to Ryan Field. This group of young men is an awfully special group. If you haven't had a chance to see them play live yet this season, I promise you: you're going to be proud of the way we play."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on being a favorite against Purdue: "We're going to stick to the same thing that we've stuck to. Not once have we used external views on this team as motivation. Bulletin board material? Nope, we're good. We've just talked about continuing to battle our tails off."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "There were mistakes made. Through those mistakes, there's growth."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the rotation for DL going into the season: "It was absolutely part of the plan. Were we as comfortable with the plan in Week One, Week Two of fall camp? Absolutely not. An intentional effort of our staff, which wasn't easy."

Mentioned double reps during the fall.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on using a timeout to substitute in Madison: "If an offense substitutes relatively late, they are going to take as much time as they possibly can to essentially enforce a delay of game."

Said that if an offense subs <20 seconds, "they are at risk of having that issue."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "Any time you start to see drill carry over into games, it's really exciting as a teacher and a coach."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on improving the turnover margin: "Credit to the offense. Have taken it really seriously. Our staff's done a great job with the ball security circuit. It's been something that's been emphasized. I know for a fact it was being emphasized prior to my arrival."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on snap counts: "There's definitely a plan that all those guys are going to play, and there's going to be a rotation. They're not on a snap count by any means. Christian [Smith] does a great job of laying that out."

Mentioned "keeping guys fresh."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on his conversation about New Ryan Field: "I'm just worried about winning football games, but what an incredible opportunity for this football team, for this University moving forward. "

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Ray Niro III: "He's such an asset. On special teams, on offense. Provides you depth. Someone else that the defense has to be concerned with."

Said that the team loves to get the ball in his hands.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the defensive line: "I would take that group against any O-line in the country."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the defensive line rotation: "Lot of hard work. Lot of humility. It takes a bunch of guys that are there to serve the best interest of the team, not their own personal statline."

Gave praise to Christian Smith and to veteran players.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
On using the mutual tape against Minnesota: "I think where the strongest carry-over for us is on defense."

Mentioned the two-high shell for both NU and UMN.

"You've got to take a strong look at that."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on playing Purdue's defense: "Honestly, I think they've done a great job offensively of identifying, 'This is how the defense that we're approaching is structured. Within our structure offensively, how can we attack that?' It's really easy to get a quick snapshot."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on better tackling: "It's really easy as a coach to step in on a Tuesday practice and say, 'Here's what we're going to emphasize.' I think it is a reflection of our guys making a conscious, intentional effort."

Also stressed the staff for preaching daily improvement.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on D.J. Vokolek: "There wasn't necessarily a specific position for him to be coaching. He's helped at all three levels of the defense."

Noted side conversations as being beneficial.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Skip Holtz: "Skip has embodied humility. A guy that walks into this facility with countless years of head coaching experience. All he's asked along the way is, 'Dave, how can I help?'"

Said he's played a "critical role" in recruiting and has "led the charge."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on offensive continuity: "We have yet to string two wins together back-to-back. It's time to go back and get back to work. I'm sure our practice habits will show that this week."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
More: "It's not just our captains. It's our leadership that permeates throughout the entire program."

Said it "starts through our captains" and "trickles down."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the importance of seniors: "Words won't do it justice. You've got to be here to truly understand it. These guys haven't flinched. They've served in their leadership role. It has nothing to do with them as individuals. It has everything to do with the program."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Said he was still "proud" of how the offense "stayed the course."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the second half offense against UW: "Going into the second half, it's something that I know our offensive staff is evaluating. What do we need to do to start fast in the second half, and close out games? You've got to credit your opponent."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that Gragg has asked the team "often" what it needs from administration.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that Gragg has been "incredibly supportive" of the Northwestern team.

"That's a credit to him."

Added that players have played a role in the coaching search.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on if he's talked to Derrick Gragg: "There hasn't. What I will say, and I'm very confident in, the people that are involved in that process, it's a critical process. They're taking the proper steps to take to ensure that the program is led in the right manner..."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Ryan Field: "That evening against Minnesota. That's a memory that will stick with you the rest of your life if you were there. That has been something this team has drawn from.

"It's only fitting and ensure that we play at our best and send it off the right way."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Senior Day: "That's what it's all about. I think one of the biggest challenges that we'll face as a team on Saturday is using that emotion to channel that into focus, and being at our best. The emotion is an indication of how much these guys care."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that Coco Azema is "day-to-day," and that the team is "hopeful" that he'll play against Purdue.

Said "absolutely" regarding if he expects Azema to play again this year.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Tracey Fuchs: "Tracey's incredible. She's been an incredible supporter of our team, of myself. I was just so impressed with their poise against a team that they had lost to."

Said the resilience "embodies" what NUFB wants to be.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the perception of NU: " I don't know what the perception is but I know what I see every day out of this group. Hard times real true characters. A lot of people have been affected, and this group has just went to work."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "Man, this group wants to ensure that we battle to have an extra opportunity to extend this season."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on addressing bowl eligibility: "It's something we addressed even prior to entering Wisconsin. We've talked about leaving no doubt. The opportunity for a bowl game is in our hands. All Wisconsin was was a performance that put us one step closer to an opportunity..."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on the #removethetag posts: "Love our team. This is a group that continues to pull together. I take that as a sign of, I must be doing something right."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "Purdue is hot right now. Offensively, operating at a really high level. Defensively, really well-coached."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun says that Northwestern has "taken seriously" the intentionality of improving every day.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun noted the importance of keeping NU's defense off the field against a "tempo operation," and the "ability to close in the second half as a team."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "Going to sound a little bit like a broken record. It was great to have the guys back in the facility."

Said they met this morning.

"Really proud of the way that we went into a hostile environment and attacked. The way that our offense performed...was critical."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun's opening statement: "Would like to start off by congratulating Tracey Fuchs and women's field hockey. Off to the Final Four. Was fortunate enough to stop down for the second half for my wife and boys yesterday. It was awesome to see the way the team continued to battle."

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun set to speak to the media shortly from the Walter Athletics Center.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Michigan and Ohio State remain on a collision course as the rest of the teams jockey for bowl eligibility. 

Around the Big Ten, Week Eleven

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern women’s basketball’s victory over Omaha showed off some real strengths, but also an issue that must be corrected as the schedule gets tougher. Here are three takeaways from Northwestern’s Sunday afternoon win.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern field hockey can get the job done in so many different ways, and that’s why the ‘Cats are headed to the Final Four for the third straight year.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
It’s hard to make Camp Randall quiet on Saturdays but the Wildcats did just that last weekend. 

Here are five takeaways from Northwestern’s convincing upset win over Wisconsin.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
McKeown realized late that this win technically makes him the winningest coach in Northwestern history. 

He closed out the presser with, "Let's have a party!"

Name: Inside NU
Content:
McKeown joked that the team really likes to take tough shots.

"We might have a couple practices where there's no ball in the gym."

Name: Inside NU
Content: McKeown on Crystal Wang: "You're going to see a lot of her. The big stage doesn't faze her. Just got to fit her game into what we're doing."

Name: Inside NU
Content: McKeown said that Mercy Ademusayo has been fighting illnesses and injuries, but noted it was great to have her on the floor against Omaha.

Name: Inside NU
Content: McKeown on Jasmine McWilliams: "She's a grind-it-out, gutty player. We need that. She'll dive on the floor, we've seen it in practice too. She gives us that spark, and hopefully it'll be contagious, because we need more people to do the same."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
McKeown on the early start: "Seeing the ball go in the basket got their confidence up. We got some steals and turnovers, and defended. 

"You've got to sustain it though, and that's what we talked about after the game."

Name: Inside NU
Content: McKeown on the ball movement: "The biggest thing is, are we getting the ball to the right people at the right time? And that's the key. I thought we made some great passes in transition. Our threes were all off pretty good passes, it's encouraging."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
McKeown noted that he saw Daley's potential in the team's road win against Iowa in 2021-22, and the team saw her growth in Spain this summer.

"'She now has the ability to bounce back from a missed shot. And she can create her own shot. I'm really proud of her."

Name: Inside NU
Content: McKeown: "Disappointed with our defense in the second half. We got a little sloppy, and we've got to clean that up."

Name: Inside NU
Content: McKeown: "We did some great things today, and we did some sloppy things today. It's not even Thanksgiving yet, so most college teams right now are trying to find themselves to see what works, and we're in the same boat."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Joe McKeown now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Walsh on fouling out twice: "I think that I need to take more accountability to play smarter defense."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mott on adjustments starting fast compared to UIC: "We did a lot of layup drills, a lot of running in practice."

Walsh noted that the team wanted to bounce back from UIC and develop an early lead to "dig in."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mott on how her confidence has grown: "Throughout my four years here, I've played under Veronica Burton, Sydney Wood and Courtney Shaw. I know what to be, because I've had them."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Walsh and Mott credit the ball movement as the biggest thing they've been impressed with offensively in the first two games.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Caileigh Walsh and Paige Mott at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The weather may be getting colder, but the Wildcats’ shooting is staying hot as they move to 2-0.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: NU 87, Omaha 69

Northwestern's 17-0 run to open the game sealed it early, and for a second-straight game, Mel Daley was nearly automatic. She led the way with 21 points on a 10-of-11 mark from the field.

Up next: No. 10 Notre Dame in South Bend.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Wang earns her first points in purple and white with a nice cut on a give-and-go. 3:30 to play, and the 'Cats are up 83-65.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Walsh fouls out for the second-straight game with five minutes to go. After another Omaha three, the NU lead is now 16.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Crystal Wang checks in with six minutes to go.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The WBB lead is now 25. Also, volleyball is winning on the road at Iowa.   Where in the world does this weekend fall on the "best weekends in the history of Northwestern Athletics" list?

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Hailey Weaver is now 3-of-4 from three. It's raining buckets in WRA.

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: That will do it for today's availability.

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH:  Fuchs "In previous Final Fours, teams could take out our one or two top players. This year, we are more balanced and consistent than the last two years."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
WBB: END OF THIRD: NU 68, Omaha 48

The Mavericks lit it up offensively in the third (9-of-14 from the field), but so did the 'Cats (10-of-17). Daley's got 19 on 9-of-10 shooting. Life is good.

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Fuchs "This has been my most rewarding year at Northwestern. To make the Final Four three years in a row, it has been really rewarding for us."

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Fuchs on Louisville: "We were excited to play this game because they are the only team that beat us."

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH; Fuchs " I knew if we could get a few corners, Wadas was going to hammer it in."

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Wadas on the game-winner: "It's a lot of calm energy. A lot of great plays put us in that position."

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Fuchs "Converting three out of five corners was the difference maker today."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Fuchs "It's really hard to go to a Final Four, and to do it three years in a row, just really proud of this team."

"This has been a rewarding season no matter what happens next."

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Tracy Fuchs, Lauren Wadas, and Ilse Tromp now at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Under five minutes to play in the third with Northwestern's lead now at 60-39. Mott has six points in the quarter, and hasn't missed. Daley and Walsh have four apiece.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Omaha sill hasn't missed from the field (that's six shots now), but neither has Daley (seven).

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Timeout Northwestern with 7:50 to go in the third. Omaha out to a hot start in the third, hitting its first four shots of the third (and beating its first quarter total in two minutes). 52-34 NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Three straight Final Fours are pretty good. Don't you think?

Name: Inside NU
Content: Third quarter is underway.

Name: Inside NU
Content: We’ll leave this here.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
HALF: Northwestern 46, Omaha 24

NU is 5-of-12 from three, and taking care of business at home. The 'Cats have forced 14 turnovers already, though they've given it away nine times. Daley leads the team with 13 points on a perfect 6-of-6.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: MEL DALEY HIT A THREE! 6-of-6 from the field!

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: THE ‘CATS ARE GOING TO THE FINAL FOUR!!!

Wadas’ goal is the difference as Northwestern holds on for a 3-2 victory. 

NU will travel to North Carolina for the semi final matchup on Friday.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Omaha really getting to the rack well. The Mavericks hit two at the line again, and NU has a 40-22 lead. 22 combined turnovers already, and there's still two minutes left in the second.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: NORTHWESTERN GOALLLLLLLLL!!

Lauren Wadas finds the back of the net with 66 seconds to go in the game!!

3-2 NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Call stands.

Corner for the Wildcats. 80 seconds left to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Northwestern draws what appears to be a corner.

Play is under review.

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Under two minutes left in regulation.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Mel Daley has 10. There is 3:52 left in the second quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: NU's shot just misses. Still 2-2.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Louisville threatens, then NU threatens, but neither get a shot off.

Still 2-2 with 4:30 left to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Walsh hits a three, and drains two at the line. However, she picks up her third foul on the other end, and McKeown subs her out. 32-16 Northwestern.

Content: FH: Yellow card for Louisville

Name: Inside NU
Content: Northwestern interim head football coach David Brain is here taking in some field hockey

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: A couple buckets from Omaha, including a three-pointer, cuts the NU lead to 27-13. Eight turnovers for the Wildcats already.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: van der Vegt with a Hugh save on the corner.

'Cats are still threatening.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Maggie Pina with her first three in purple and white!

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Corner for NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
WBB: END OF FIRST: Northwestern 24, Omaha 8

Legitimately one of the most dominant first quarters of basketball I've ever watched. 10 turnovers and a 2-of-13 shooting clip from Omaha. Hailey Weaver, Mel Daley and Paige Mott had more points than the entire team for minutes.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: GOAL NORTHWESTERN!!

The 'Cats answer right back on another strike from Ilse Tromp off a corner.

2-2 with 12:30 left to play in regulation.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Green Card for Louisville.

Cardinal defender takes a shot to the face, but is ok.

Wildcats with a corner.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Call on the field stands.

Corner for the Cardinals, and Aimee Plumb sneaks it pass Skubisz for a goal.

Cardinals lead 2-1 with one quarter left to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Scramble for the ball around the goal, but Skubisz is able to push it away.

However, Louisville is awarded a corner. 

The play is under review.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: BREAKING: Omaha has scored. An offensive rebound off the second missed FT leads to a three, and it's 17-4.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Weaver with five straight points. It's 17-0. Will Omaha now 0-of-6 from the field, but they'll get a chance at points from the line.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Mel Daley in the corner for a midrange jumper is the surest thing since the sun coming up. It's 12-0.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Great save by van der Vegt prevents Northwestern from breaking the tie.

'Cats have all the momentum in the second half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: FH: Another corner for the 'Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
WBB: Walsh and Mott are taking full advantage of mismatches in the post, and in a hurry, it's 10-0 Northwestern after a Lau bucket on a fastbreak.

Timeout Omaha with 7:43 left in the first.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The shot misses the net wide right.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Corner for Northwestern.

'Cats had one corner before this, and it worked out pretty well.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Northwestern hits the ground running. Mel Daley drains a midrange J (because of course), and then Hailey Weaver gets an and-one layup to go in transition. 4-0 'Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FH: Green card called on the Cardinals, but NU was unable to capitalize.

'Cats have been in the attacking third for most of the second half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: WBB: Mott wins the tip, and we're off from Welsh-Ryan.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
WBB: Starting for the 'Cats:

Caroline Lau
Hailey Weaver
Mel Daley
Paige Mott
Caileigh Walsh

Same as Thursday night's win over UIC.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Masked Lau automatic triple-double incoming

Name: Inside NU
Content: We are in the building for ’s matinee with Omaha, where they’ll try to go 2-0! Follow along for tweets and coverage (we’ll designate WBB and FH tweets as such)

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Shot from Halsey is saved with less than 60 seconds left in the clock. 

At the half, Northwestern and Louisville are all even at 1-1. 

Cardinals outshot the ‘Cats 5-2 in the half and had three more corners than NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Skubisz with two huge saves to keep the game tied. 

1-1 with 2:20 left to play in the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Corner for Louisville. 

Neither team has a shot in goal in the second quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Call is overturned. 

Louisville gains possession.

Name: Inside NU
Content: We are in the building for ’s matinee with Omaha, where they’ll try to go 2-0! Follow along for tweets and coverage (we’ll designate WBB and FH tweets as such)

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Penalty corner for Northwestern. 

Play is under review.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
‘Cats have been threatening in the offensive third, but Louisville has been able to clear the ball each time. 

After giving up an opening goal, NU seems to have settled in.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
At the end of the first quarter, ‘Cats and Cardinals are all knotted at 1. 

Only three combined shots in the quarter, but two found the net.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
GOAL NORTHWESTERN!!

Ilse Tromp buries one to the back of the net to even this one up. 

Louisville’s lead lasted all of 2 minutes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Penalty corner for Northwestern.

Content:
Another corner for the Cardinals, and they draw a third corner on the play. 

On the third corner,  Louisville’s finds the back of the net to get on the board. 

1-0 Cardinals with 5:08 left in the first quarter.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Skubisz makes the save and the ‘Cats clear it out. 

Cardinals have put pressure on NU early in the game.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Penalty corner for Louisville.

Still knotted up at 0

Name: Inside NU
Content: We are off at Lakeside Field.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Northwestern’s lone loss this season came at the hands of the Cardinals. 

‘Cats looking for revenge and to punch their ticket to the final four for the third year in a row.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
‘Cats are set to take on Louisville with a trip to the Final Four on the line!

Follow along for updates.

Name: Inside NU
Content: “It was made clear inside Camp Randall on Saturday afternoon: David Braun has earned the right to be Northwestern’s permanent head football coach. It is time to remove the interim tag,” writes.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Good night from Camp Randall

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant's message to Northwestern fans: "It's a really big game. Come out and support us. We're going to put on a show. We're really confident right now. These last two games are really huge for us. We have a 1-0 mindset."

Name: Inside NU
Content: On helping him prepare: "Giving him any tips or knowledge that I have... Whether it's gameday or throughout the week. He does the same thing for me. It's a two-way road."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on Brendan Sullivan: "He's a great competitor. Really, really good quarterback. He's one to look out for in the years to come. Really smart. Really athletic. Throws a great ball."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant on better OL play: "They played a phenomenal game. I'm so happy for those guys. They work their butts off. I don't really feel banged up at all. I feel pretty good."

Said he won't have to "waddle to the bathroom" anymore.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on his experiences: "I never expected to go through all that I've gone through when I went into college. I'm honestly happy that I've gone through all of it. I feel like I've grown into a man. It's a great story for my career."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on what changed at halftime: "I don't know. It's a little frustrating. We want to keep our foot on the gas, and keep scoring."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant: "I think it was just really good coaching all week. We had a plan for some looks we hadn't seen much all season. It was really cool to see."

On the touchdowns: "Those were just the guys making a play. Cam won one-on-one." Mentioned a pick on Henning's TD.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant on possibly being bowl eligible: "I think it would mean a lot. I've been lucky to experience a bowl game every year of my career, and some of those guys haven't had that experience."

Mentioned how beneficial it can be for young players to develop during extra practice.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on starting hot: "It's big. It was big to just go out there and make a statement. Just score consecutively, and not take our foot off the gas."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant said today was a "great atmosphere."

In terms of spreading the ball around, he attributed it to confidence.

"I trust all those guys out there. I know they're going to make a play."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant said he felt dialed in after the first drive.

"I think just getting that first drive and those first couple completions really just gives you the confidence to go out there and do it the rest of the game."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on Braun's growth: "He's never wavered. He stepped in in a really difficult situation. Taken us to this point. He's the guy that everyone looks to to lead and motivate. We're going to follow him wherever he goes. We love him as our head coach. We love him."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant said he got "swarmed" by former Cincinnati strength coaches and players as he left the field.

Noted "similarities" in terms of Fickell's defense here at Wisconsin, but also new elements.

"It was cool to see some of that stuff translate."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on Fickell: "I didn't talk to him at all this week. I have nothing but respect for that guy. He gave me the chance to come back to Cincinnati. He's a really good coach and leader. He's going to do great things at Wisconsin."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on any worry about rust: "I think maybe if I was a redshirt freshman. I'm so experienced. I think all of that plays into helping me."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant on his role the last few weeks: "I think just seeing it from a different perspective. You kind of pick up on things that you might not see when you're playing. Learn about being more of a leader, honestly. I learned how to lead off the field."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant on when he felt like he was ready to play: "I think last week, we kind of started a throwing progression. We kind of slowly eased into it. We did a really good job of managing that."

Last weekend, he knew "I'm back."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ben Bryant now at the podium.

On his rehab process: "It was frustrating not being able to be out there with my teammates. Injuries suck. It was so nice to get back out there."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher on Bryant: "We didn't focus on it much. Ben and Sully are great players. We focus on the defense and believe that they will get it done on the offensive side."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher on his message for next week's home game: "Come out. Be loud. Support us. We're battling each and every week. We're doing out best to get wins for our fans."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Soares on his growth this season: "Guys like Bryce and Xander have been pushing me to be better. Just being able to stay the course has been big."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Soares on his first sack celebration: "I thought about it, but I did not execute it."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Soares on Jump Around: "Having fun. That's the most important part of the game, is really just embrace the moments."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher on playing with a lead as a defense: "I mean, it's huge. You have that insurance knowing that the offense is playing really well."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Soares on his deflection: "Thought process is just get a stop. Don't let them score. We always preach, 'Threes don't beat us.'"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher said that having "11 guys on the same page" was critical as to why the defense succeeded.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Soares said that the team is "focusing on coming together as a team," and attributed that as to why the result was different this year against the Badgers.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher also noted that the team wants Braun to "be here for a long time," and that the "team wants to battle with him each week."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Gallagher on learning under Braun: "He's come in and done a great job installing his system as a DC. Something that we love to go out and execute the plan he's putting the place in for us."

Said he's done an "absolutely phenomenal job" as head coach.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Soares said that it's his dad's birthday, and wanted to get him a sack as a present.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Gallagher on Wisconsin's rushing attack: "I think that's a credit to their D-line. It really came down to guys doing their job."

Mentioned fitting runs and staying in gaps.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Gallagher on winning against Wisconsin: "It was huge. Something we preached all week was going on the road and getting a win."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryce Gallagher and Kenny Soares II will head to the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That ends Braun's media availability.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on locker room celebrations: "The dance moves already got busted out. I'll leave it to other guys to judge my rhythm and expertises. There's nothing more exciting than celebrating a win."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Jump Around: "They were just having fun. A bunch of college guys that love playing the game of football. Love playing together."

Called it "one of those iconic things in college football," and said it was played during practice.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on third down success: "It was great to see them staying ahead of the chains. It was efficient. The ball was coming out on time. Efficiency has the ability to lead to explosiveness."

Name: Inside NU
Content: "He continues to set the standard."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Bryant playing against Fickell: "I don't know if preparation changes. Ben's a competitor. That dude was laser-focused all week. He was laser-focused to get back as soon as he could."

Name: Inside NU
Content: More: "I'm talking football sometimes. A lot of times, we're just talking life. It's tangible."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun: "What I've learned over the years is that, at the end of the day, we coach people. We coach student-athletes. We don't coach football players."

Said "meeting people where they're at" is the "ultimate blessing," something he relishes as a head coach.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun: "This team is full of purpose-driven dudes."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on if this road win meant more: "Honestly, no."

Said that the team "put four quarters together."

"What means the most to me is that I got the opportunity to do it with those guys."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said he doesn't have an update on Coco Azema's status.

"We're hoping he's back on the field sooner than later."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Porter: "I think our o-line did a good job moving the line of scrimmage. I was really proud of the way all those guys ran."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on Jaheem Joseph: "So stinking proud of him. Jaheem's not someone that may have been satisfied with his number of snaps. He continued to own his role, continued to prepare."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on defensive improvement: "Again, it's guys that have continued to improve fundamentally. That haven't gotten so caught up in scheme."

Mentioned tackling and ball-out breaks.

"I've got to point out the leadership on that defense."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on reducing penalties: "It's critical. It makes sure that you keep yourself ahead of the chains offensively."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on containing Wisconsin's run defense: "That O-line of Wisconsin is really good. Coach Smith, Coach McGarigle of the front-seven did a really good job of the preparation this week."

Stressed finishing plays.

"They weren't going to allow themselves to be blocked."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on the offensive line: "Just a group that's continued to tune everything out. Go back to work."

Emphasized a first-quarter pass play that created a clean pocket. Also praised the pass pro work of the running backs, such as Tre Tyus.

"It takes everyone to protect the QB."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on bowl eligibility: "We're in a great spot. We talked as a team on Tuesday about leaving no doubt. At the end of the day, we took in the right direction in terms of leaving no doubt."

Said that that manifests by the "way that you prepare."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on winning in Madison: "We talked about complementary football. The best thing to do against a tempo offense like Wisconsin is play with a lead."

Says this group's confidence is "real"

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun mentioned Bryant's third-down completion to Johnson in the end zone as emphasizing him being locked in.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that the team was going to "take it one day at a time" regarding Bryant's injury. Noted his improved confidence as the week went along.

Name: Inside NU
Content: On if he's earned the full-time job: "That's not up to me."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun on winning five games in his first year: "It means that I'm so stinking proud of this group of guys. So proud of this staff. So proud of the way that everyone has continued to battle."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on being 5-5: "It's a bunch of purpose-driven people...that know why they're doing what they're doing."

Said the team's "purpose is greater than self."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that last year's game against Wisconsin was "never" brought up.

"We knew we just had to be rooted in our purpose."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on coaching in Camp Randall: "Big Ten football. It's pretty awesome."

Said he's been here for multiple years, and that he "knew the environment that existed here."

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun on Ben Bryant's return: "What I saw was a young man that didn't miss a beat. Tuesday's practice, we're easing him back into things. He's on time, he's confident."

Noted that he has a "ton of maturity" due to "staying locked in."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun said that the "challenge" will be to move on to Purdue.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Braun said that the team "attacked" in a "really difficult environment to play in."

"As a coach, and as a coaching staff, we couldn't be more proud."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Braun's opening statement: "Had an opportunity to visit with the team after the game. So proud of this group for so many reasons. I think what we saw out there this afternoon was a result of a group that showed up to the facility on Monday, learned from the Iowa game..."

Name: Inside NU
Content: David Braun set to speak to the media shortly from Madison.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The ‘Cats are jumping around after this one.

Name: Inside NU
Content: We’ll take a whole lot more of that.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FINAL: Northwestern 24, Wisconsin 10

In classic David Braun fashion, the Wildcats responded in a monumental way after losing at Wrigley Field.

NU was buoyed by the return of Ben Bryant, who went 18-for-26 with three total touchdowns. The 'Cats' defense held tall all day.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Wisconsin finally finds the end zone on a Jackson Aker touchdown. It's 24-10 Wildcats with 11 seconds left.

Name: Inside NU
Content: The Badgers are at the Northwestern 32, but we're officially in garbage time.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Henning runs out of bounds on third-and-12, and Northwestern will punt with 4:45 and counting.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mordecai overthrows Pauling on third-and-17. Heard was in coverage, and the Badgers will punt with 6:37.

This one is wraps.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Theran Johnson beautifully breaks up a ball intended for C.J. Williams. Textbook coverage from the junior.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Wisconsin's Jack Nelson called for another hold. That's the fifth penalty on Luke Fickell's bunch. Ball is backed up to the UW 46.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Joseph tracks down Bell after a gain of three.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Badgers going up-tempo. Pauling has his seventh catch. UW at the Northwestern 47.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mordecai dumps it off to Aker for nine.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mordecai hits Bryson Green for a first down. Badgers at their own 39.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Another offside on Northwestern makes it second-and-5, but UW is running out of time. Just 8:40 left with the Badgers down 21.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant's pass falls incomplete, and Renner will punt again.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter goes nowhere on two straight carries, and the 'Cats are facing a third-and-seven.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
FUMBLE!!

Heard punches it away from a scrambling Mordecai, and Hollis falls on it.

'Cats will take over on their own 29 leading by 21 points.

This one is getting late quickly, and the Badger fans are heading to the exits.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Yacamelli eludes multiple 'Cats and picks up five.

After a completion the play before, Badgers in 'Cats territory.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Acker gets just enough for a first down.

Badgers nearing midfield.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Third-and-two for Wisconsin.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Second effort from Acker gives the Badgers a fresh set of downs.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Yacamelli picks up four, but it is third-and-one for the Badgers.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Sean McLaughlin bats down the first down pass, but NU gets called for an offside on the ensuing play.

2nd-and-five.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Renner uncorks one to the Badgers' 22-yard line.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant is nearly intercepted, but the ball falls incomplete.

Renner to punt again.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
THE PRESS BOX IS LITERALLY SHAKING

This is awesome

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant flings it to Gordon for a short gain, and the 'Cats will face a third-and-five when the fourth quarter begins.

Northwestern is still ahead 24-3 with one quarter left to play.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant finds Johnson across the middle for another first down.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Wisconsin took too long subbing, so the referee would not let Bryant snap the ball.

With the play clock expiring, Braun had to burn his first timeout of the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Johnson gets a favorable spot and it is a first down for the Wildcats.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Tyus picks up four yards on two carries, and the 'Cats are facing another third down deep in their own territory.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Coco Azema has been ruled OUT for the remainder of the game, per NU athletics.

Aidan Hubbard is questionable to return.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Henning with a big return, but it is called back for a block in the back.

Jaheem Joseph did everything he could to get out of the way but clipped the gunner.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Aidan Hubbard gets home!

No. 91 brings down Mordecai for his fifth sack in three games, and the Badgers have to punt.

Hubbard was down after the play and is being attended to by the training staff.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mordecai find Pauling for five.

Third-and-9 incoming

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Hold on the Badgers moves them back 10 yards.

Jack Nelson gets called for his second penalty.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bad punt from Renner takes a 'Cats bounce, but Wisconsin will start near midfield again.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter gets stuffed on third down, and the Wildcats will send the punting unit out again.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Johnson gets low and hauls in a seven-yard pass from Bryant.

Third-and-3.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter once again goes nowhere on first down.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
THE 'CATS STAND TALL.

On fourth down, Mordecai's pass is incomplete, and the Wildcats take over on their own eight.

Theran Johnson with the tight coverage.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
After a nice catch on second down, Mordecai's pass is batted down by Soares.

4th down.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
False start on Badgers send them back five yards.

2nd-and-13.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
QB draw from Mordecai goes for 19 yards.

First-and-10 from the Wildcats' 14.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Yacamelli picks up six on the carry.

Third-and-six from NU's 33.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mordecai escapes for a first down, but a hold on the Badgers negates the run.

2nd-and-11 for Wisconsin.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Officials overturn the call on the field.

First down Wisconsin.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Pauling makes the catch but is marked short of the marker.

Fourth-and-one for Wisconsin.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
It's been all Cade Yacamelli in the backfield for the Badgers.

Braelon Allen only has three carries on the day.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Wisconsin calls for a fair catch at the 'Cats' 48.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant is sacked.

Northwestern will punt for the first time on the game.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter goes nowhere on first down, and Bryant can't handle the snap on second down.

'Cats facing a third-and-16.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Henning returns the ball to the 25 to open up the second half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Credit to  for pointing out that there have been 439 total yards of offense in the first half of a Big Ten West game.

'Cats will kneel it out and head to the locker room up 24-3.

Ben Bryant is 14-for-20 for 169 yards and two touchdowns

Boos are getting loud.

27 seconds remaining.

34 seconds remaining.

Olsen splits the uprights.

24-3 NU with one minute to play in the half.

Bryant scrambles for a couple yards but is stopped well short of the goal line.

Jack Olsen on to attempt a 27-yard field goal.

Bryant sails on hitch to Kirtz.

Third-and-goal from Wisconsin's 13.

Backside TE screen converts the third down.

NU is 10/10 on third down.

First-and-goal for the Wildcats.

Content:
Bryant hit when he threw, but the ball just hits the ground before the Badgers got to it.

Run by Porter sets up third-and-7 at the 20.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Big block from Caleb Tiernan allows Henning to weasel his way to the marker for a first down.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Lausch keeps it for minimal gain, and it is third-and-five NU from Wisconsin's 32.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
EVERYTHING IS COMING UP 'CATS.

A.J. Henning makes a circus catch for a 41-yard gain. Northwestern is already in field goal range.

This is hilarious.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Azema is out of the medical tent and was testing the injured leg with the medical staff on the sideline.

Wildcats can breathe a sigh of relief.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Badgers can not capitalize on the big play, stalling out at the 'Cats' 23.

Wisconsin's 40-yard field goal attempt was no good. 

Still 21-3 NU, and the boos are getting loud at Camp Randall.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mordecai hits Will Pauling for a 33-yard completion.

Badgers already at the 25-yard line.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Azema is being helped off the field by the training staff. He is barely able to put any weight on his right leg.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Coco Azema is down on the field, holding his knee.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Northwestern has three offensive drives.

All have been 9+ plays and ended in touchdowns.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
TOUCHDOWN WILDCATS!!

Bryant, with a free rusher in his face, lofts one to Johnson, who climbs the ladder for a 24-yard touchdown.

21-3 Wildcats with 6:41 left in the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter picks up four on two runs, and it is third-and-6 for the 'Cats.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ray Niro hauls in a 19-yard pass from Bryant.

'Cats inside the 30.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Great blitz pickup from the 'Cats, and Bryant finds Henning for a first down.

Wildcats are 7/7 on third down.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
After a first down run from Himon, Bryant's pass to Kirtz falls incomplete.

Third down.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
JOESPH HIMON WHEELS!

The sophomore takes the outside handoff 34-yards and the Wildcats are nearly at midfield.

What. Is. Happening.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Great open-field tackle by Jaheem Joseph to prevent the first down.

Wisconsin to punt, much to the chagrin of the Badger faithful.

'Cats take over at their own 10.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Third-and-four now for Wisconsin.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Mordecai finds C.J. Williams for a first down, and the Badgers are inside 'Cats territory.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Anthony takes another short kick from Helms out to Wisconsin's 37-yard line.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
TOUCHDOWN NORTHWESTERN!

Play fake from Bryant fools everyone, including myself, and he walks into the end zone.

14-3 'Cats with 12:54 left in the half.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter gets to the one but is ruled short of the goal line.

Let the flashbacks begin.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter pushes ahead for a first down on a zone read from Jack Lausch.

First-and-goal NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant just gets it over the defender to Kirtz for a five-yard gain to close out the first quarter.

Wildcats will start the second quarter at Wisconsin's 12.

Northwestern leads 7-3.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Tre Tyus gets dragged down by his facemask, and the Wildcats get a free 15 yards.

First-and-10 NU at the 17.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter picks up another first down on the ground.

'Cats back inside Badger territory.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant hits Johnson on a snag for six yards and a new set of downs.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant scrambles for no gain and takes a massive pop on the sideline. On the next play, porter rushes for six.

Third-and-4 for NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Badgers pick up eight on second down, but Mordecai's third-down pass falls incomplete.

Henning picks up a couple on the return, and NU will start at its own 32.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Rod Heard II seals the edge and Allen's run goes nowhere.

2nd-and-10.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Badgers will start at the 20 after Niro makes the tackle on Kickoff.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Ben Bryant

Name: Inside NU
Content:
TOUCHDOWN NORTHWESTERN.

Wisconsin loses sight of A.J. Henning, and waltzed into the end zone for a 23-yard touchdown.

7-3 NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant scrambles for two.

Third-and-long for Northwestern at UW's 23.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Badgers sniff out a screen and wallop Himon in the backfield.

Second-and-13.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant hits Kirtz for seven yards and a fresh set of downs.

NU's drive is pushing five minutes.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Handoff to Henning goes nowhere.

Third-and-five.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Himon takes a screen for five.

2nd-and-five at UW's 30.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Porter rips off a 17-yard run into Badgers' territory.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Porter gets his first carry of the game and picks up three.

Third-and-two NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant connects with Cam Johnson on first down for five yards.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ray Niro hauls in the shallow cross and breaks a tackle to move the chains.

First-and-10 NU at its 39.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant hits Kirtz in the hands on a deep out route, but the Kirtz drops it.

Third-and-four for NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Bryant comes out slinging on first down, finding Kirtz for a six-yard gain.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ben Bryant is in the huddle for the 'Cats' opening drive.

It's official: He's back.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Kick is good.

Badgers lead the 'Cats 3-0 less than five minutes into the game.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Kenny Soares Jr. brings down Mordecai from behind for a sack.

Badgers will have to settle for a 33-yard attempt.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mueller meets Jackson Ackers in the whole for a minimal gain.

Third-and-long.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Hollis breaks up a fade in the end zone.

2nd-and-10 incoming.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Two screens to Allen goes for a fresh set of downs.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mordecai finds Anthony on a deep crosser for 34 yards.

Wisconsin already in the red zone.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Will Pauling absorbs a shot from Coco Azema, but he holds on for the catch.

First down Wisconsin

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Najee Story gets his hands on Braelon Allen first before the rest of the 'Cats join in.

Third down incoming

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Mordecai's first pass is complete for a gain of five.

2nd-and-five.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Henry Helms boots it to the 10, and Vinny Anthony runs it back to the 28-yard line.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Northwestern has won the toss and deferred to the second half.

Tanner Mordecai and Co. up first

Name: Inside NU
Content: At least two big injured players back for Wisconsin in Mordecai and Dike. Set to be Mordecai's first start since Oct. 14.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Bryant working with the first team offense 30 minutes before kickoff. 

Looks like he is back under center for NU.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Ben Bryant is back in pads and warming up. 

No announcement on who will be under center for the ‘Cats today

Name: Inside NU
Content: We have you covered before the ‘Cats and Badgers kick off.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
When Boo Buie picked up his fourth foul with 9:12 left and Dayton shooting well, Northwestern had to find a new way to win in a big game. It did.

As  writes, “The only certainty so far is that Northwestern still hasn’t run out of surprises.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: Our staffers favor the Badgers in today’s matchup, but there’s optimism that the Wildcats can win in Madison for the first time since 2015.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Good news in terms of Bryant's injury progress, but still uncertainty regarding who gets the nod for Northwestern today.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That’s all from Welsh-Ryan.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Barnhizer on his inspiration for his motor: “As a sophomore, I had to do that to get on the court. It’s a part of me. I’m never gonna lose what got me on to the floor.”

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Langborg on Berry: “When he hit those threes, our entire team lit up.”

Barnhizer: “He’s the most energetic guy on our team.”

Name: Inside NU
Content: Langborg on the defensive performance: "It was a step up, but there were too many threes."

Name: Inside NU
Content: Barnhizer credited the balance with the offensive rebounding and not allowing a bunch of fastbreak points to coaching. Notes that the team usually crashes three, and did a good job of understanding the situation  each shot.

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Barnhizer on Martinelli: “He’s huge. Good thing about Nick is, he loves ball. The problem was this summer, the coaches had to tell him to chill out.”

Compared Martinelli’s role this year to his own last year.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Langborg and Barnhizer at the podium.

Name: Inside NU
Content: That’s all from Collins.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins on dealing with defensive pressure: “I thought we did pretty darn good, with only 7 turnovers. We’re we perfect? No, but we didn’t turn the ball over.”

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on defending Da’Ron Holmes: “We came into the gameplan trying to get the ball out of his hands. They did a great job of hurting us, and we called off our double-teams.”

Credited Brea and Santos for their shooting.

Name: Inside NU
Content: Collins especially praised Langborg’s aggressiveness after Buie picked up his fourth foul. “We needed that.”

Name: Inside NU
Content:
Collins on the fan support: "It was awesome. I got a rush of energy when I walked out on the floor. You get a llittle bounce in your step.

"I hope we can make this where it doesn't have to be a Dayton coming in here. It was a fun night."
